  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3276" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <opener>Dear D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>. Schuchardt,</opener>

        <p>the March number of the Etudes Historiques et Religieuses du Diocèse de Bayonne, which I received from <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.121">
Pau</placeName> on Saturday, contains a continuation of my Dechepare. The Editor tells me that my translation is barbare. Then why did he not request me to alter it? He sent me two sets of proofs. He particularly attacks je prie which occurs twice as the translation of othoy. The printer has slightly separated ya and çadaçu on the 2nd page. of course they ought to be joined. The Editor without consulting me has printed St. Jean le Vieux instead of St Michel le Vieux. Has he found out then that Dechepare went to that parish? also not understanding himself that <foreign
            xml:lang="eu">
çaquiztan</foreign> contains mihi as indirect object, he has changed my “me profitiez” into “en profitiez”. I did not notice this in the proof. I hope he will go on with the rest of the religious part of this author. I have read all of <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5454">Stempf</persName>s glossary down to the January number of the R. de L. which appeared only last Saturday. I find some misprints, some mistakes of definition, and a few eccentricities e.g. õ put in as a separate item. My Bascomania called my attention to <foreign
            xml:lang="grc">
εβασκαvε</foreign> in Galatians just as it had to <foreign
            xml:lang="grc">
βασκ᾽ιθι</foreign> in Homer,<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">'go! haste!', vgl. <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.6124">
Maltby, Edward (1830): A New and Complete Greek Gradus, or, Poetical Lexicon of the Greek Language</ref>
            </bibl>, s.v. <foreign xml:lang="el">
βασκω</foreign>.</note> to bascu a violet in <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.3143">Sard</ref>, to <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">bask</ref> = very dry in Jamiesons Scottish Dictionary, to bask in English, to bask = together in <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.893">Albanian</ref>, to basca = nausea in <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.779">Spanish</ref> and hot in <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.3143">Sardinian</ref>, etc: etc: but I put it in partly to shew that <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref> is a fascinating study, partly to incite the Basques to study <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.838">Greek</ref>. few even of their clergy do so. J. I. de Arana knows it. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1195">Bréal</persName> says that the volume of his philological society for this year and next also is quite full, but that if I joined the society perhaps the committee would accept part of my work for later on I have finished Champneys History of English 1893, and am going on with Historical outlines of English syntax by <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1896">Leon Kellner</persName>. I suppose gorri may be connected with <foreign
            xml:lang="eu">goritzen</foreign> since heat produces redness. In old <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref> and in the writing of some unlearned people now I believe double rr and single r are interchanged. Euskara 13 will appear in April.</p>
        <p>
          <note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz oben, über der ersten und zwischen den ersten beiden Zeilen.</note>
          <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2939">Vinson</persName> translates <foreign xml:lang="eu">judubaren</foreign> by les juifs: it is du juif. p. 396 Bibliography.</p>
        <p>
          <note n="3" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der rechten Seite.</note> D'Urte's Basque text will be printed this year in <placeName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.9">Oxford</placeName>.</p>
        <closer>
          <note n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der linken Seite.</note>
          <dateline>21 March.</dateline>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson</persName>.</signed>
          <dateline>12 Rue de la Sorbonne. 1893</dateline>
        </closer>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
      </div>
